rders herself must be a picturesque character, the wife of a taxi-cab operator, who acted a her own counsel in the case and apparently her own press agent. She proved to be a good one in both cases.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Russell|first=Horace|date=1939|title=The Borders Case|journal=The Journal of Land & Public Utility Economics|volume=15|issue=2|pages=225\u2013227|doi=10.2307/3158131|jstor=3158131|issn=1548-9000}}</ref> \"'Portia' Borders became the heroine of thousands of Britons who pay high rents for grimy kennels or find their shiny new houses falling apart,\" explained ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine in 1939.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,761772,00.html|title=Foreign News: After Elsy|date=1939-07-31|work=Time|access-date=2020-03-21|language=en-US|issn=0040-781X}}</ref> She appealed the case up to the [[House of Lords]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47069911/mrs-borders-to-appeal/|title=Mrs. Borders to Appeal|date=1939-02-14|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-21|pages=11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47070281/mrs-borderss-appeal-allowed/|title=Mrs. Borders's Appeal Allowed|date=1940-01-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-21|url-status=live|pages=3|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> but it was finally lost in 1941.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47069725/mrs-borders-loses-her-appeal/|title=Mrs. Borders Loses Her Appeal|date=1941-05-10|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-21|url-status=live|pages=5|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nIn a related case, Borders successfully represented her husband in a [[Defamation|libel]] case brought by the housing society.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47070520/verdict-for-mr-borders/|title=Verdict for Mr. Borders|date=1939-03-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-21|url-status=live|pages=10|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nElsy Borders was a member of the [[Communist Party of Great Britain|Communist party]], and helped to form the Federation of Tenants\u2019 and Residents\u2019 Association (FTRA).<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsshopper.co.uk/news/10688529.west-wickham-heroine-from-borders-of-insanity/|title=West Wickham heroine from 'borders of insanity'|last=Ogley|first=Bob|date=20 September 2013|website=News Shopper|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> They led a mortgage strike in [[England]], joined by 3,000 home-owners. The FTRA held its first national convention in 1939, in Birmingham. That year, an amendment to the Building Societies Act, introduced by [[Ellen Wilkinson]], addressed some of the FTRA's concerns; however, the Act's final revision increased protections for the building societies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/property/3291336/Inside-story-insanity.html|title=Inside story: insanity|last=Wilkes|first=Roger|date=24 July 2001|website=The Telegraph|publisher=|via=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishpathe.com/video/VLVA5SWQ1QPQ2YNG5ZBPLN0DHCCLH-POLITICS-GOVERNMENT-BILL-AGAINST-JERRY-BUILDING-PLANNED/query/Jerry|title=Politics: Government Bill Against Jerry-Building Planned|last=|first=|date=6 March 1939|website=British Path\u00e9|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nElsy Kreher married James Walter (Jim) Borders in 1926; her husband was a London cabby. They had a daughter, Pamela, born in 1930. The couple jokingly called their house \"Insanity\", and themselves \"the Borders of Insanity.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> The Borders moved away from London in 1940, and divorced in 1944. Elsy and her daughter moved to [[Exeter]] during [[World War II]].  Elsy Borders died in 1971, aged 66 years, in Exeter.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*Graham Stevenson (2